ups. For example, the annual rates of decline for total CVD mortality for 2000-2011 were 3.69\% (3.48\% to 3.89\%) for males and 3.98\% (3.81\% to 4.14\%) for females; for 2011-2014, the rates were 0.23\% (-0.71\% to 1.16\%) and 1.17\% (0.41\% to 1.93\%), respectively. The gap between HD and cancer mortality persisted.{$<$}/p{$><$}h3{$>$}Conclusions and Relevance{$<$}/h3{$><$}p{$>$}Deceleration in the decline of all CVD, HD, and stroke mortality rates has occurred since 2011. If this trend continues, strategic goals for lowering the burden of CVD set by the American Heart Association and the Million Hearts Initiative may not be reached.{$<$}/p{$>$}},
